'''Abraham Arden Brill''' (October 12, 1874 – March 2, 1948) was an Austrian-born [[psychiatrist]] who spent almost his entire adult life in the United States. He was the first psychoanalyst to practice in the United States and the first translator of Freud into English.<ref name=mishne>{{cite book|last=Mishne|first=Judith Marks|title=The Evolution and Application of Clinical Theory: Perspective from Four Psychologies|year=1993|publisher=The Free Press|location=NY|page=33|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=bS21abc4GYUC&pg=PA33&}}</ref> 

==Education==
Brill was born in [[Kańczuga]], [[Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria|Austrian Galicia]]. He arrived in the United States alone at the age of 15. He graduated from [[New York University]] in 1901 and obtained his M.D. from [[Columbia University]] in 1903.<ref name=nytobit/> He spent the next 4 years working at [[Central Islip Psychiatric Center|Central Islip State Hospital]] on Long Island.<ref name=nytobit/> 

==Career==
After studying with [[Eugen Bleurer]] in Zurich, Switzerland,<ref name=mishne/> He met Freud, with whom he maintained a correspondence until Freud's death in 1939.<ref name=mishne/> He returned to the United States in 1908 to become one of the earliest and most active exponents of [[psychoanalysis]], being the first to translate into English most of the major works of [[Freud]], as well as books by [[Jung]]. His first translation of Freud appeared in 1909 as "Some Papers on Hysteria''.<ref name=nytobit>{{cite news|title=Dr. A.A. Brill Dies; Psychiatrist, 73|url=http://query.nytimes.com/mem/archive/pdf?res=F20911F73E54177A93C1A91788D85F4C8485F9|accessdate=March 8, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=March 3, 1948}}</ref>  He campaigned for academic recognition of his field, lectured at [[Columbia University]], and became clinical professor of psychiatry at [[New York University]].<ref name=mishne/> He maintained a psychoanalytic practice as well.

In 1911 he founded the [[New York Psychoanalytic Society]] (or Institute) and later helped found the [[American Psychoanalytic Association]].<ref name=mishne/> The library of the New York Psychoanalytic Institute is named in his honor.<ref name=mishne/> In 1929, following Freud's lead, as head of the New York Psychoanalytic Society, he sanctioned the introduction of lay analysts to the profession, which had previously restricted its ranks to medical professionals.<ref>{{cite book |last=Muckenhoupt |first=Margaret|title=Sigmund Freud: Explorer of the Unconscious|year=1997|publisher=Oxford University Press |location=NY |page=133|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=CkYxpgNybv0C&pg=PA133&}}</ref> During the 1930s he played a key role in finding employment for psychiatric professionals exiled from Nazi Europe.<ref>{{cite book|last=Friedman|first=Lawrence Jacob |title=Identity's Architect: A Biography of Erik H. Erikson|year=1999|publisher=Harvard University Press |page=111 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=tFJvyOpFJtUC&pg=PA111&}}</ref> 

Once sympathetic to homosexuals, he revised his views and wrote in 1940 that "even so-called classical inverts are not entirely free from some paranoid traits".<ref>{{cite book|last=Terry|first=Jennifer|title=An American Obsession: Science, Medicine, and Homosexuality in Modern Society|year=1999|publisher=University of Chicago Press |pages=292-3 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=qRMJ_d-yUWYC&pg=PA292&}}</ref> 

[[Edward Bernays|E. L. Bernays]] consulted with Brill on the subject of women's smoking.{{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}

He married Dr. K. Rose Owen. They had two children. He died at [[Mount Sinai Hospital, New York|Mount Sinai Hospital]] in New York in March 2, 1948.<ref name=nytobit/>

